Blockages.

A blockage is an invisible barrier that stops the player with a spoken message instead of a solid surface. Step toward the area it covers and you're bounced back while a line of text you wrote is spoken — the air is too thick to push through, the bridge is out, you are not permitted beyond this point. Blockages are the entity for fencing off part of a map and telling the player why, without building anything they can hear or touch.

A blockage is an invisible, message-carrying boundary. Its sibling, the wall, is a solid physical barrier built from a tile theme; see the walls topic for when a real obstruction fits better than a spoken one.

How a blockage works.

A blockage fills a rectangular area. The instant the player tries to step into that area, the blockage speaks its text and bounces them back out, so they never actually enter it. It has no sound of its own beyond the spoken line, no surface, and no health — it can't be bumped along like a wall and it can't be destroyed. It simply refuses entry and explains itself each time.

Because the message plays every time the player runs into it, a blockage doubles as a sign you can't ignore: a hint, a warning, or a bit of narration delivered exactly when the player tries to go somewhere they shouldn't.

How a blockage differs from a wall.

The two both stop the player, so the distinction is worth stating plainly:

A blockage is an invisible boundary. It has no tile, no sound theme, and no health; it can't be destroyed; and instead of a bump it speaks a custom message and bounces the player back.
A wall is solid construction. It's built from a tile theme, makes a bump sound, has health, can be destroyed (optionally leaving debris), and can be made transparent to the scanning camera. The player feels it as a physical surface.

Reach for a wall when the obstruction is part of the world the player should hear and maybe break through. Reach for a blockage when you just need to seal off an area and tell the player why, with nothing physical in the way.

Blockage fields.

The blockage form takes the following:

Coordinates. A minimum and maximum x and a minimum and maximum y (and a minimum and maximum z on 3d maps), marking the rectangular area the player is kept out of. A blockage always spans a range, even on 2d maps.

Text. The message spoken each time the player runs into the blockage.

A blockage has no sound theme, no health, and no other settings — its area and its message are the whole of it.

Authoring blockages by hand.

If you edit main.sif directly, a blockage is: blockage minx maxx miny maxy "text". On 3d maps a minimum and maximum z follow the y pair: blockage minx maxx miny maxy minz maxz "text". The text is wrapped in double quotes so the message may contain spaces.
